<h2>Chapter 7: Common Mistakes That Kill Local SEO Campaigns &#123;#ch7&#125;</h2>
<p>For every success story, there are 10 businesses that tried local SEO and gave up. Here are the mistakes that kill campaigns before they produce results.</p>
<h3>Mistake 1: Expecting Results in 30 Days</h3>
<p>Local SEO takes 3-6 months to show meaningful results. Some businesses see early wins from GBP optimization within 30 days. But sustainable ranking improvements require consistent effort over time.</p>
<p>The businesses that quit at 60 days were usually 30 days away from a breakthrough. Local SEO is a compounding strategy. Early effort builds foundation. Results accelerate after month 3.</p>
<h3>Mistake 2: Inconsistent NAP Information</h3>
<p>A business has their address as "123 Main St" on their website, "123 Main Street" on Yelp, and "123 Main St. Suite 100" on Facebook. Google sees these as three different businesses. Rankings suffer.</p>
<p>Audit every listing. Use exactly the same format everywhere. This is tedious but essential.</p>
<h3>Mistake 3: Ignoring Mobile Experience</h3>
<p>76% of local searches happen on mobile. If your website loads slowly, has tiny buttons, or requires pinching and zooming, you are losing customers.</p>
<p>Test your site on a phone. Check Core Web Vitals. Fix issues. Mobile experience is a ranking factor and a conversion factor.</p>
<h3>Mistake 4: Keyword Stuffing Location Pages</h3>
<p>Some businesses create 50 location pages with the same content, just swapping city names. Google detects this as duplicate content and penalizes the site.</p>
<p>Each location page needs unique content. Mention local landmarks. Include neighborhood-specific details. Add original photos from that area. Write for humans, not search engines.</p>
<h3>Mistake 5: Neglecting Review Management</h3>
<p>A business gets 50 reviews and stops asking. Competitors keep generating reviews and overtake them. Or they get a bad review and ignore it, letting it sit unanswered for months.</p>
<p>Review generation is ongoing. Respond to every review. Address negative reviews professionally. Use feedback to improve service.</p>
<h3>Mistake 6: Focusing on Traffic Instead of Conversions</h3>
<p>A business ranks #1 for a high-volume keyword but gets few calls because the page has no phone number, no clear call to action, and a confusing layout.</p>
<p>Traffic without conversion is vanity. Every local page needs a clear next step: call, book, visit, or request a quote. Make it obvious and easy.</p>
<h3>Mistake 7: Not Tracking the Right Metrics</h3>
<p>Businesses track rankings but not calls. They track traffic but not appointments. They cannot connect SEO effort to business results.</p>
